	<h1>Language Installation Instructions<br />
	Programming Language Paradigms</h1> 

	
	<h4> Installing Groovy in Eclipse</h4> 
	Groovy requires Java, so you need to have a version available (1.4 or greater is required).  
	If you do not already have it installed follow this <b><a href="http://www.rose-hulman.edu/class/csse/resources/JavaDevKit/installation.htm">Java</a></b> installation tutorial for instructions on how to do so.
	There is a Groovy plugin for the Eclipse development environment v3.4 and up. To install it, 
	<br /><br />
	<ol class="steps">
		<li>
			Open eclipse. 
		</li>
		<li>
			Navigate to <b>Help</b> then to <b>Software Updates</b>
		</li>
		<li>
			Click on the <b>Available Software</b> and click on the <b> Add Site...</b> button and add one of the following sources.
		</li>
			<ol type="a">
				<li>
					Location for Eclipse v3.4: <p class="link">http://ci.repository.codehaus.org/greclipse/snapshot/e34/</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					Location for Eclipse v3.5: <p class="link">http://ci.repository.codehaus.org/greclipse/snapshot/e35/</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		<br />
		<img src="images\install_1.jpg" />
		<br /><br />
		<li>
			You should now see an entry <i>Groovy update Site.</i>
		</li>
		<li>
			Expand it and select <i>Groovy-Eclipse Plugin.</i>
		</li>
		<br /><br />
		<img src="images\install_2.jpg" />
		<br /><br />
		<li>
			Click <b>Install</b> and click through until the installation is complete
		</li>
	</ol>
	<br />
	<h4> Testing the Groovy Installation in Eclipse</h4> 
	Here we will validate that the Groovy plugin has been succesffuly installed.
	<ol class="steps">
		<li>
			Make sure that you are in the Java Perspective in Eclipse
		</li>
		<li>
			Click on the <i>Create New Project Wizard</i> button and select Groovy Project and give your new project a title.
		</li>
		<li>
			Right click on the src folder in the project and select <i>New</i> and add a new blank file.  
			What you name the file is of your choice, but you must give it a .groovy extension.
		</li>
		<li>
			In the new groovy file add the following line of code. 
			<p class="code">
			println "Hello, World!"
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			Save the file and right-click on it.  Click <i>Run As</i> and select Groovy.
		</li>
	</ol>
	<br />
	<h4>Alternative to Using Eclipse</h4>
	If you do not have a compatable version of Eclipse for the Groovy plugin 
	or for whatever matter simply do not want to use Eclipse, follow these instructions to setup the Groovy console.  
	Groovy requires Java, so you need to have a version available (1.4 or greater is required). 
	If you do not already have it installed follow this <b><a href="http://www.rose-hulman.edu/class/csse/resources/JavaDevKit/installation.htm">Java</a></b> installation tutorial for instructions on how to do so.
	<ol class="steps">
	<li>
		Setup Java environment variables on Windows.
		<ol class="a">
			<li>
				Go to your control panel and open up <i>System Properties</i>.
			</li>
			<li>
				Click on the <i>Advanced</i> tab and then on the <i>Environment Variables</i> button.
			</li>
			<li>
				Add a new System variable with the name JAVA_HOME with the value of the directory Java was installed in (point it to the <i>folder</i>).
			</li>
		</ol>
	</li>
		<li>
			Follow this <b><a href="http://dist.codehaus.org/groovy/distributions/installers/windows/nsis/groovy-1.6.4-installer.exe">Download Link</a></b>
			to get the windows installer for Groovy 1.6.4.
		</li>
		<li>
			Run the executable and follow the typical installation instructions until you get to <i>Environment Variables</i> setup.
		</li>
		<li>
			Setting the Groovy environment variables on Windows.
			<ol class="a">
				<li>
					The Groovy installer will set these for you.  Your task is simply to verify that it is named GROOVY_HOME and that the
					path points to the location of your installation.
				</li>
				<img src="images\install_3.jpg" />
				<li>
					Start a command prompt, and type "set" and hit return to see that your Java and Groovy environment variables were set correctly.
				</li>
				</ol>
		</li>
		<li>
			Once the installation is finished, open a Groovy Console and type in the following line of code.
			<p class="code">
			println "Hello, World!"
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			Click on the <i>Execute Groovy Script</i> button (far-right).
		</li>
		<img src="images\install_4.jpg" />
	</ol>
	<br />
	
	
